Below is a **complete, self‑contained example** that shows how you can expose a high‑performance C++ block iterator to Python while still letting the Python user supply a per‑block callback.  
The design follows the pattern used by pandas/Polars – the user can either:

* iterate over the collection in a Pythonic `for block in chain:` loop, or  
* call a single `chain.foreach(callback)` method that runs the callback for every block (the hot path).

The binding is written with **pybind11** because it gives you a clean, type‑safe wrapper around the C++ objects and lets you control the GIL (Global Interpreter Lock) very precisely – the key to keeping the hot loop fast.

---

## 1. C++ side – a tiny “real‑world” stub

```cpp
// blocksci_binding.cpp
//
// This file contains:
//   * a minimal Block representation (just enough for the demo)
//   * a BlockChain class that owns a C++ iterator over blocks
//   * the pybind11 binding code
//
// In the real BlockSci library the iterator would walk the on‑disk
// deployment index; here we simulate it with a simple vector of
// synthetic blocks so that the example can be compiled and run
// without any external data.
//
// -------------------------------------------------------------

#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <pybind11/functional.h>
#include <pybind11/stl.h>
#include <vector>
#include <string>
#include <cstdint>
#include <chrono>
#include <thread>

namespace py = pybind11;

// ----------------------------------------------------------------
// 1️⃣  Minimal Block object – mirrors the real BlockSci block API
// ----------------------------------------------------------------
class Block {
public:
    // In the real library these would be read from disk.
    uint64_t height_;
    std::string hash_;
    uint64_t timestamp_;        // Unix epoch seconds
    uint64_t tx_count_;         // Number of transactions in this block

    Block(uint64_t h, std::string hash, uint64_t ts, uint64_t txs)
        : height_(h), hash_(std::move(hash)), timestamp_(ts), tx_count_(txs) {}

    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    // Expose a few read‑only properties – they are cheap to fetch.
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    uint64_t height()   const { return height_; }
    const std::string& hash() const { return hash_; }
    uint64_t timestamp() const { return timestamp_; }
    uint64_t tx_count() const { return tx_count_; }

    // A pretty‑print for debugging / REPL
    std::string repr() const {
        return "<Block height=" + std::to_string(height_) +
               " hash=" + hash_ +
               " txs=" + std::to_string(tx_count_) + ">";
    }
};

// ----------------------------------------------------------------
// 2️⃣  BlockChain – owns the iterator and provides the hot API
// ----------------------------------------------------------------
class BlockChain {
public:
    // In the real library the constructor would open the deployment
    // directory and build a fast iterator over the on‑disk index.
    explicit BlockChain(const std::string& path) : path_(path) {
        // ---- Simulated data -------------------------------------------------
        // Build a vector of 10 000 synthetic blocks (you can bump this to
        // millions for a real benchmark).  The iterator will just walk this
        // vector.
        const size_t N = 10'000;               // change to 800'000'000 for a real test
        blocks_.reserve(N);
        for (size_t i = 0; i < N; ++i) {
            blocks_.emplace_back(
                i,                                 // height
                "0000000000000000" + std::to_string(i), // fake hash
                1609459200 + i * 600,              // timestamp (Jan 1 2021 + 10 min per block)
                (i % 5) + 1                         // tx count (1‑5)
            );
        }
        // --------------------------------------------------------------------
    }

    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    // 2.1  Python iterator protocol – enables:  for block in chain:
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    class iterator {
    public:
        using inner_iterator = std::vector<Block>::const_iterator;

        explicit iterator(inner_iterator it) : it_(it) {}

        const Block& operator*() const { return *it_; }
        const Block* operator->() const { return &(*it_); }

        iterator& operator++() { ++it_; return *this; }
        bool operator!=(const iterator& other) const { return it_ != other.it_; }

    private:
        inner_iterator it_;
    };

    iterator begin() const { return iterator(blocks_.cbegin()); }
    iterator end()   const { return iterator(blocks_.cend()); }

    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    // 2.2  Hot path – run a Python callable for every block.
    //      The GIL is released for the bulk of the loop; it is only
    //      reacquired when we need to call the user function.
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    void foreach(py::function py_cb) const {
        // Keep a reference to the Python callable so it does not get GC'd
        // while we are iterating.
        py::object cb = py_cb;

        // The iterator itself is pure C++, so we can run it without the GIL.
        // We only acquire the GIL right before invoking the Python callback.
        for (const Block& blk : blocks_) {
            // ------------------------------------------------------------
            // 1) Acquire the GIL for the callback
            // ------------------------------------------------------------
            py::gil_scoped_acquire acquire;

            // 2) Call the Python function.  We pass a *copy* of the block
            //    because the Block object is cheap to copy (just a few ints
            //    and a short string).  Copying avoids lifetime issues.
            cb(Block(blk));   // <-- user code runs here

            // 3) GIL is released automatically when `acquire` goes out of scope.
        }
    }

    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    // 2.3  Small convenience – return the number of blocks.
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    size_t size() const { return blocks_.size(); }

    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    // 2.4  A debug `repr` for the Chain object.
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    std::string repr() const {
        return "<BlockChain path=\"" + path_ + "\" blocks=" + std::to_string(blocks_.size()) + ">";
    }

private:
    std::string path_;
    std::vector<Block> blocks_;          // In real BlockSci this would be a custom iterator.
};

// ----------------------------------------------------------------
// 3️⃣  pybind11 module definition
// ----------------------------------------------------------------
PYBIND11_MODULE(blocksci, m) {
    m.doc() = R"pbdoc(
        Python bindings for a (simulated) BlockSci deployment.
        The real library ships a C++ iterator over 800 M blocks; this
        example shows how to expose that iterator while letting users
        run arbitrary Python code per block.

        Example
        -------
        >>> import blocksci
        >>> chain = blocksci.BlockChain("/path/to/deployment")
        >>> print(chain)                      # <BlockChain path="/path/to/deployment" blocks=800000000>
        >>> # 1️⃣ Iterate in a Pythonic way
        >>> for blk in chain:
        ...     print(blk.height, blk.tx_count)
        >>> # 2️⃣ Or use the hot `foreach` helper (the GIL is released for the
        >>> #    inner loop, so this is as fast as a pure‑C++ walk)
        >>> def my_cb(block):
        ...     # do something heavy, e.g. NumPy work, DB write, etc.
        ...     if block.height % 1_000_000 == 0:
        ...         print("Reached", block.height)
        >>> chain.foreach(my_cb)
    )pbdoc";

    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    // Block class – expose read‑only properties and a nice __repr__
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    py::class_<Block>(m, "Block", R"pbdoc(
        A lightweight view of a Bitcoin block.

        Attributes
        ----------
        height : int
            Block height (0‑based)
        hash : str
            The block hash (hex string)
        timestamp : int
            Unix epoch seconds
        tx_count : int
            Number of transactions in the block
    )pbdoc")
        .def_property_readonly("height",    &Block::height)
        .def_property_readonly("hash",      &Block::hash)
        .def_property_readonly("timestamp", &Block::timestamp)
        .def_property_readonly("tx_count",  &Block::tx_count)
        .def("__repr__", &Block::repr);

    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    // BlockChain class – iterator protocol + hot foreach()
    // ----------------------------------------------------------------
    py::class_<BlockChain>(m, "BlockChain", R"pbdoc(
        A collection of blocks loaded from a BlockSci deployment.

        The object behaves like an iterable of :class:`Block` and also
        provides a ``foreach`` method that runs a Python callable for
        each block while keeping the inner loop in C++ (the GIL is
        released for the bulk of the iteration).
    )pbdoc")
        .def(py::init<std::string>(),
             py::arg("path"),
             "Create a BlockChain view for the deployment at *path*.")
        .def("__repr__", &BlockChain::repr)
        .def("__len__", &BlockChain::size)
        // ----------------------------------------------------------------
        // Iterator protocol – enables `for block in chain:`
        // ----------------------------------------------------------------
        .def("__iter__", [](const BlockChain& self) {
            // Return a Python iterator that calls the C++ iterator's ++/*
            return py::make_iterator(self.begin(), self.end());
        }, py::keep_alive<0, 1>() /* Keep chain alive while iterator exists */)
        // ----------------------------------------------------------------
        // Hot foreach() – the user supplies a Python callable.
        // ----------------------------------------------------------------
        .def("foreach",
             &BlockChain::foreach,
             py::arg("callback"),
             R"pbdoc(
                Call *callback* once for every block in the chain.

                The underlying C++ loop runs without the GIL; the GIL is
                reacquired only when invoking *callback*.  This makes the
                hot path as fast as a pure‑C++ walk while still allowing
                arbitrary Python code to be executed per block.

                Parameters
                ----------
                callback : Callable[[Block], Any]
                    Function that receives a :class:`Block`.  Its return
                    value is ignored.
             )pbdoc");
}
```

### What the binding does for you

| Feature | How it works | Why it matters for performance |
|---------|--------------|--------------------------------|
| **Python iterator (`for blk in chain:`)** | `BlockChain.__iter__` returns a `py::make_iterator` that wraps the C++ iterator. | No extra Python call‑stack per block – the iterator yields a *reference* to an existing `Block` object, so the loop is essentially a direct C++ walk. |
| **`foreach(callback)`** | The C++ loop runs with the GIL released; only when `callback` is called we reacquire the GIL (`py::gil_scoped_acquire`). | The costly part (reading the block, doing any C++ work) stays in native code. The Python function is called *once per block* but the overhead of lock‑management is minimal. |
| **Zero‑copy `Block` objects** | The `Block` class holds only POD data + a small `std::string`. Copying a block is cheap (≈ 40 bytes). | Guarantees that the Python side sees a stable object without needing to manage lifetimes of internal buffers. |
| **`py::keep_alive<0, 1>()`** | Guarantees the `BlockChain` stays alive while the iterator lives. | Prevents use‑after‑free bugs that would otherwise be hard to debug. |
| **`py::functional.h`** | Allows a Python `Callable` to be stored as a `py::function` and called from C++. | No manual `PyObject_Call` boilerplate and proper reference‑count handling. |

